    "Multiple Inheritance" in Java. The interface isn't simply a "more pure" form of abstract class. It has higher purpose than that. Because an interface has no implementation at all- That is, there is no storage associated with an interface - there is nothing to prevent many interfaces from being combined. This is valuable because there are times when you need to say: "an x is an a and a b and a c". In C++, this act of combining multiple class interfaces is called multiple inheritance, and it carries with it some sticky baggage because each class can have an implementation. In Java, you can perform the same act but only one of the classes can have an implementation, so the problems seen in C++ do not occur with Java when combining multiple interfaces. Tester class for the inheritance/interface hierarchy
